 Yes.

190
00:18:01,340 --> 00:18:04,780
 You know, life is will to power and nothing else.

191
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:13,460
 I also don't think Nietzsche treats all styles the same.

192
00:18:14,260 --> 00:18:21,600
 You know, I mean, like the style of monotheism is obviously critiqued more so than the style of polytheism.

193
00:18:21,920 --> 00:18:22,640
 Yeah, yeah.

194
00:18:22,860 --> 00:18:30,220
 Monotheism in general leads to the reduction and sterilization of life, which is sort of the entire project is thrust against that.

195
00:18:30,500 --> 00:18:32,340
 Which is still a sign of its life.

196
00:18:32,480 --> 00:18:32,620
 Yeah.

197
00:18:32,880 --> 00:18:33,080
 Right.

198
00:18:33,140 --> 00:18:34,100
 It's still a sign of life.

199
00:18:34,340 --> 00:18:35,060
 Yeah, no, you're right.

200
00:18:35,300 --> 00:18:35,440
 Sure.

201
00:18:35,540 --> 00:18:37,280
 A life for a different type of –

202
00:18:37,560 --> 00:18:39,960
 Right, it's a health for a different type of life.

203
00:18:40,420 --> 00:18:44,540
 And so that's where it's like he's fascinated by Jesus in the Antichrist, for instance.

204
00:18:44,700 --> 00:18:47,020
 Like Jesus is an interesting character.

205
00:18:47,260 --> 00:18:50,460
 Christianity, on the other hand, Paul, on the other hand, you know what I mean?

206
00:18:50,520 --> 00:18:53,960
 Like it's a – you got to deal with each of these things differently.

207
00:18:54,180 --> 00:18:56,700
 Like religion isn't one thing, you know?

208
00:18:56,780 --> 00:19:01,100
 So, I mean, obviously, look at his fascination with the Greeks, you know?

209
00:19:01,520 --> 00:19:06,300
 I mean, it's – this is not anti-religion at all.

210
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:08,980
 And it's always more – it's always more complex than that.

211
00:19:09,040 --> 00:19:10,720
 But it's always – it's always hard.

212
00:19:10,820 --> 00:19:25,880
 I have to remind myself in certain cases, and for me it is particularly theological ones, where I have to like say, hey, this isn't that person – this isn't that person's inability or incapacity to move past a dogmatism.

213
00:19:26,280 --> 00:19:32,600
 Right, it's in fact my dogmatism that sees that in them, right?

214
00:19:32,640 --> 00:19:47,240
 And it's very – for me it's very hard and requires will, a willful effort on my part to hear those things as something other than, well, she just believes in the dumb, you know, man in the sky.

215
00:19:47,240 --> 00:19:51,660
 As a general, I always have really uninteresting interpretations of religion.

216
00:19:51,820 --> 00:19:56,740
 I don't necessarily judge people, but I always treat it as some version of a coping mechanism.

217
00:19:56,920 --> 00:19:57,020
 Yeah.

218
00:19:57,100 --> 00:19:57,440
 Oh, yeah.

219
00:19:57,660 --> 00:19:58,920
 And I don't know how –

220
00:19:58,920 --> 00:19:59,060
 Same thing.

221
00:19:59,560 --> 00:19:59,820
 Yeah.

222
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:02,340
 I don't know how else to really conceptualize.

223
00:20:02,440 --> 00:20:04,100
 I mean, I guess just another style.

224
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:04,840
 Yeah.

225
00:20:04,980 --> 00:20:06,140
 But it's just –

226
00:20:06,140 --> 00:20:12,920
 But this is where I'll come back to what you were saying though, Nate, is that I've – one thing that I've started to do a little bit is less –

227
00:20:12,920 --> 00:20:19,920
 Think about it as an error that, you know, they're just – or as an intellectual sort of inability to go somewhere.

228
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:20,120
 Dishonesty.

229
00:20:20,320 --> 00:20:20,680
 That's how I –

230
00:20:20,680 --> 00:20:21,580
 Dishonesty, yeah.

231
00:20:21,580 --> 00:20:28,780
 That – and less in terms of sort of like the, well, why can't you just reason yourself to point A to point B when it's so obviously there?

232
00:20:28,880 --> 00:20:54,080
 I turn to the coping mechanism thing, but this is also where, you know, I'll maintain a certain kind of hierarchy or something in styles of life or expressions of will in that this is one that just tends to attack and judge and destroy the world in order to carve out an impoverished version of life.

233
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:55,400
 Transcendence.

234
00:20:55,400 --> 00:20:55,480
 Transcendence.

235
00:20:55,480 --> 00:20:55,780
 It is.

236
00:20:55,780 --> 00:21:14,040
 I mean, it imports transcendence in like, you know, even though it is truly obviously very difficult to really think imminence, but nevertheless, like that – the ways in which the kind of – I don't know, at least to me, the default that transcendence is superiority.

237
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:14,480
 Yeah.

238
00:21:14,620 --> 00:21:30,760
 Is I think the thing that I'm always just like – it's – I've been reading Nietzsche too long because to me when people talk about things beyond this world as constitutive elements of this world, I just always – I really do hear a hatred of life.

239
00:21:30,860 --> 00:21:31,000
 Yeah.

240
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:38,740
 Like I really do hear a denigration of the phenomenal or something like that.

241
00:21:38,740 --> 00:21:49,080
 And what's even the most irritating – at the theological level, then at least when you're talking to the theologian, it becomes an object of play sometimes and you can mess around with it.

242
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:53,440
 But – or at least you're sort of like operating within the intellectual.

243
00:21:54,580 --> 00:22:11,860
 But the way that it gets expressed in the everydayness of one's life and what I find like when someone's not interested in thinking the theological at all, there's an orientation to life as labor and toil and suffering and sin.

244
00:22:11,860 --> 00:22:16,980
 And that is – that's just sad to be around.

245
00:22:17,420 --> 00:22:27,920
 It's just sad to have the world transformed into that thing over and over again, which makes me think of – you know, this is one of the early Christian lines.

246
00:22:28,540 --> 00:22:31,120
 The dangerous – this is 130, a dangerous decision.

247
00:22:31,520 --> 00:22:36,420
 The Christian decision to find the world ugly and bad has made the world ugly and bad.

248
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:37,820
 Right, right.

249
00:22:38,240 --> 00:23:01,100
 Which goes back to the very first aphorism you brought us to, Nate, is that the attribution of cause and effect or the interpretation itself, it's not a – whether it's true or false is the least interesting – it's the force of will, the sense, the evaluative strength with which it is turned into a world-producing machine.

250
00:23:01,760 --> 00:23:06,760
 I mean, in some ways, that's all I ever said to Boo Boo about Barad, right?

251
00:23:06,980 --> 00:23:11,440
 The willingness – the interpretation of the world as bad has made the world bad.

252
00:23:11,560 --> 00:23:20,520
 And it's like the interpretation of Barad as a – you know, an – you know, a material – a reductive materialist makes a reductive materialist, right?

253
00:23:21,120 --> 00:23:21,360
 Right.

254
00:23:21,760 --> 00:23:33,060
 And I do have that – I mean, this is the way in which, you know, I think I'm an idealist in this way because I really do believe that nothing is anything.

255
00:23:33,480 --> 00:23:33,780
 Yeah.

256
00:23:35,160 --> 00:23:36,100
 Necessarily, right?

257
00:23:36,340 --> 00:23:40,240
 Like, and that anything can be done.

258
00:23:40,360 --> 00:23:47,580
 Like, I really do believe in principle that one could, for instance – I remember Nealon and I used to talk about this years ago.

259
00:23:47,660 --> 00:23:50,940
 It's like, Hegel is not about negation at all.

260
00:23:51,060 --> 00:23:53,740
 That's just an epiphenomenal manifestation, right?

261
00:23:53,780 --> 00:23:58,900
 Like, that just seems incomprehensible to me, right, at this moment.

262
00:23:58,900 --> 00:24:01,680
 Or, like, Heidegger isn't actually interested in Big B being.

263
00:24:02,360 --> 00:24:02,860
 You know, whatever.

264
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:11,420
 You just take things that are just, like, super obvious that, of course, they're – and you're like, I believe there are ways of engaging this that that's not necessary.

265
00:24:12,400 --> 00:24:12,620
 You know?

266
00:24:13,300 --> 00:24:13,660
 Yeah.

267
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:19,640
 I mean, and then part of that – I mean, just because you mentioned, Barad, just on that line – I was thinking about this the other day.

268
00:24:19,640 --> 00:24:24,960
 But that whole – most of that project was fueled by resentment.

269
00:24:26,040 --> 00:24:26,840
 Yeah, no, yeah.

270
00:24:27,420 --> 00:24:32,760
 Well, I mean, and I think – I guess it's good that I've realized that retroactively –

271
00:24:32,760 --> 00:24:34,480
 That's why we started this whole podcast.

272
00:24:34,580 --> 00:24:35,040
 Don't you remember?

273
00:24:35,460 --> 00:24:39,240
 Like, it was – I mean, I'm sure Nathaniel remembers this.

274
00:24:39,320 --> 00:24:47,820
 But after you did your – you defended your prospectus and I was like, this is one of the best prospectus – well, this is the best prospectus that I've ever read in my years.

275
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:52,920
 And it just pisses me off because it's so – it's so reductive.

276
00:24:53,160 --> 00:24:57,200
 Like, it's so intent on proving something to be wrong and bad.

277
00:24:57,620 --> 00:25:02,180
 And, you know, that was the constant – like, that's what started this whole thing is, like, it could be cool.

278
00:25:02,520 --> 00:25:03,520
 So –

279
00:25:03,520 --> 00:25:03,960
 Yeah.

280
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:10,540
 I guess I just – I don't blame myself at the time because I think that's what generated the material.

281
00:25:10,700 --> 00:25:10,840
 Yeah.

282
00:25:11,040 --> 00:25:16,420
 But ultimately, it's not what I'm interested in anymore is that orientation towards the tech.

283
00:25:16,580 --> 00:25:16,820
 Right.

284
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:17,120
 Yeah.

285
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:18,040
 And it's nothing to blame.

286
00:25:18,140 --> 00:25:22,660
 It's not to blame because it's like – you think of the irony of me saying – and it pissed me off, right?

287
00:25:22,720 --> 00:25:24,260
 That you were pissed off, right?

288
00:25:24,500 --> 00:25:29,560
 So, like, I'm – I mean, it's not like, oh, it's a stage and you grew out of it.

289
00:25:29,640 --> 00:25:40,080
 It's just a – it's just like at certain moments that disposition is oriented towards some kinds of things and other things become background or they become a different kind of color in relationship to it.

290
00:25:40,080 --> 00:25:50,320
 Or just take that growth model that you just dismissed, John, but now subtract the transcendence from it rather than, like, there's a natural progression and you went from one immature stage into another.

291
00:25:50,420 --> 00:25:51,540
 No, you – well, you did.

292
00:25:51,620 --> 00:26:01,460
 You went through – you went through a stage and that stage produced something unexpected that actually now allows you to reevaluate what came before.

293
00:26:01,560 --> 00:26:03,560
 It wasn't the natural next step, right?

294
00:26:03,900 --> 00:26:04,200
 Right.

295
00:26:04,200 --> 00:26:11,080
 Well, I never – I never – also never would have gotten to this orientation with Deleuze if I hadn't passed through that orientation abroad.

296
00:26:11,380 --> 00:26:20,180
 So, it points again to the importance of style like you're talking about because I don't agree – I don't disagree with the content of my arguments when I reread them.

297
00:26:20,180 --> 00:26:24,860
 I mean, I just – I chafe against the tone and the style of those interventions.

298
00:26:24,860 --> 00:26:25,280
 The smell.

299
00:26:25,520 --> 00:26:25,960
 Yeah.

300
00:26:26,460 --> 00:26:27,680
 Yeah, the smell of the intervention.

301
00:26:27,700 --> 00:26:28,040
 The smell, right.

302
00:26:28,340 --> 00:26:28,560
 Yeah.

303
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:30,260
 They smell offensively Hegelian books.

304
00:26:30,260 --> 00:26:31,200
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

305
00:26:33,940 --> 00:26:35,240
 That's why you did this.

306
00:26:35,380 --> 00:26:38,980
 You wanted you and Nietzsche to have written offensively Hegelian books.

307
00:26:39,800 --> 00:26:40,580
 You did too.

308
00:26:41,320 --> 00:26:41,760
 Yeah.

309
00:26:43,400 --> 00:26:44,180
 That's good.

310
00:26:44,320 --> 00:26:44,960
 That's good.

311
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:49,260
 But it's – Nathaniel, I think, you know, it's such a good point to say.

312
00:26:49,940 --> 00:27:07,760
 What happens if you think of education not as the progressive heading towards the platonic light at the end of the cave or whatever, but simply as a sort of differential movement along an economy of affect or whatever, right?

313
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:11,980
 Like that to me is – and that is really I think how I think of it.

314
00:27:12,020 --> 00:27:12,900
 Like that's what we're doing.

315
00:27:12,900 --> 00:27:14,540
 We're not making people smarter.

316
00:27:14,980 --> 00:27:28,840
 We're shifting them into different potential dispositions which will alter the ways that they interact in the world and it will make – I mean that – and it is – it's growth in a sense.

317
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:34,640
 But it's not – but it's not growth as like positive development.

318
00:27:34,800 --> 00:27:38,780
 It's just – it's transformational, you know.

319
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:41,660
 I think that is what it means to make people smarter though.

320
00:27:43,480 --> 00:27:44,960
 Yeah, it's part of it for sure.

321
00:27:44,960 --> 00:27:52,920
 It's to have them – the smarter is that they've moved through different dispositional – that they have an array of different dispositions available to them.

322
00:27:52,920 --> 00:28:01,860
 That they've had to go through the work and the shifting of self in order to be able to go through those moves.

323
00:28:02,280 --> 00:28:09,480
 The problem is is that you can't say ahead of time what those things are going to be and that's the problem with –

324
00:28:09,480 --> 00:28:15,520
 So that's like saying – so that's like saying intelligence, smart, making people smarter.

325
00:28:15,740 --> 00:28:20,200
 Intelligence is really about the capacity to learn.

326
00:28:20,780 --> 00:28:20,980
 Yeah.

327
00:28:21,080 --> 00:28:27,520
 Not about the acquisition of a content or not about – you know – it's not about knowledge actually.

328
00:28:27,540 --> 00:28:32,180
 Yeah, it's not about knowledge or knowledge is at best – it's an instrumental side effect.

329
00:28:32,180 --> 00:28:38,420
 The secondary – it's a secondary content that's only important for the styles that it provokes.

330
00:28:38,940 --> 00:28:40,100
 Exactly, right?

331
00:28:40,160 --> 00:28:41,140
 You have to work with this.

332
00:28:41,140 --> 00:28:42,380
 Man, someone should write a book on that.

333
00:28:42,600 --> 00:28:44,180
 You have to work with it very carefully.

334
00:28:44,840 --> 00:28:53,260
 So this is the other thing is that that sort of – that trajectory that you're laying out seems kind of chaotic and meandering.

335
00:28:53,260 --> 00:29:03,960
 And it feels wishy-washy as opposed to the structure of a traditional model that says, you know, you start with A and then you go to B and then C and then out of the platonic cave.

336
00:29:03,960 --> 00:29:05,580
 You progress to the next stage.

337
00:29:05,680 --> 00:29:06,060
 That's happening.

338
00:29:06,580 --> 00:29:10,800
 But that – but see – but that has a much harder time I think actually hanging together.

339
00:29:10,900 --> 00:29:20,100
 I think that falls subject to Zeno's paradox because it's like how do you ever accomplish stage one and then realize it and move transition into stage two?

340
00:29:20,100 --> 00:29:27,520
 There's a – there's – because you're dealing with static things called stages and the movement across them becomes problematic.

341
00:29:27,840 --> 00:29:38,460
 I think there's actually far more rigor and attentiveness to that thing that's supposedly meandering when you engage thoroughly rigorously with whatever it is.

342
00:29:38,560 --> 00:30:02,740
 And then whatever that stage is, which you cannot predict, I would wager to say is far more thoughtfully, rigorously, attentively attached to the previous stage than it could ever be if it was mapped out.

343
00:30:02,740 --> 00:30:05,660
 Why did you – why did you shake your head when I said that's Hegel?

344
00:30:06,620 --> 00:30:14,080
 Oh, I just mean because I don't – I don't always subscribe to the teleological – the simple teleological version of Hegel.

345
00:30:14,440 --> 00:30:19,360
 But isn't it – I mean isn't it – it's hard for me to understand how the phenomenology is not progressive.

346
00:30:20,960 --> 00:30:25,520
 I mean it certainly is, but then it's weirdly – like I mean you know the story.

347
00:30:25,620 --> 00:30:27,580
 Like you get to the end and you're just back at the beginning.

348
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:28,320
 Right.

349
00:30:28,320 --> 00:30:29,800
 Like everything – yeah.

350
00:30:30,160 --> 00:30:33,120
 I mean it's like none of – it's recursive.

351
00:30:33,380 --> 00:30:37,140
 So it's not simply point A to point B on a diagonal line.

352
00:30:37,460 --> 00:30:37,700
 Right.

353
00:30:37,860 --> 00:30:42,600
 It's like you think you're going up, but then once you actually reach the summit, you're just back at the beginning.

354
00:30:42,900 --> 00:30:43,460
 Right, right, right.

355
00:30:43,460 --> 00:30:48,900
 So I mean it's a little more complicated than just stages, but anyway.

356
00:30:48,900 --> 00:31:08,620
 My question is on back to this conversation is how do you resist this kind of dispositional attunement just becoming co-opted by the institution where it becomes something like a learning outcome, like rhetorical flexibility or like contextual awareness.

357
00:31:08,620 --> 00:31:14,120
 In case of what you'll say, yeah, metacritical, critical thinking or whatever and critical thinking becomes this –

358
00:31:14,120 --> 00:31:19,440
 Or maybe you don't – maybe you're not worried about it becoming – maybe it becoming co-opted is just part of the – you know what I mean?

359
00:31:19,560 --> 00:31:19,860
 Like how do you –

360
00:31:19,860 --> 00:31:25,900
 Whatever becomes co-optive, you know, it becomes co-opted and then it just becomes material to, you know, work with.

361
00:31:25,940 --> 00:31:30,220
 It becomes a bit of the calcified whatever to work with.

362
00:31:30,220 --> 00:31:30,440
 Right.

363
00:31:31,300 --> 00:31:38,700
 I'm just wondering if there's a way to put that on a syllabus where it's not simply another thing on a syllabus.

364
00:31:39,600 --> 00:31:46,460
 Yeah, see, I never – I feel like I – this is – that's in some ways at the heart of my teaching and yet it would never be on the syllabus.

365
00:31:46,940 --> 00:31:52,700
 It's only – and I also think it's only available to like small classes, by the way.

366
00:31:52,700 --> 00:32:00,460
 I do think that there are sort of constraints to it is that like what would that look like when you have 250 anonymous students?

367
00:32:00,480 --> 00:32:02,480
 I'm doing it for 250 asynchronous people.

368
00:32:02,700 --> 00:32:12,040
 Like and let me say I hang my hat for this whole like – the whole impetus behind this class is not that they're learning science fiction.

369
00:32:12,860 --> 00:32:17,500
 Like I mean I've – it's super clear that like we're not teaching – I'm not teaching you the great stuff.

370
00:32:17,560 --> 00:32:18,660
 I'm not even teaching you the good stuff.

371
00:32:18,760 --> 00:32:23,120
 Like I lead a lot of times with, hey, the movie you're going to watch this week is really bad.

372
00:32:23,380 --> 00:32:25,040
 You know, it's RoboCop, right?

373
00:32:25,120 --> 00:32:27,120
 Like it's not – this is not a good movie.

374
00:32:27,800 --> 00:32:30,880
 That doesn't, however, mean that we can't think in relationship to it.

375
00:32:30,880 --> 00:32:38,360
 So I hang my hat for this 200-person anonymous class on the vacuous phrase critical thinking.

376
00:32:38,580 --> 00:32:38,640
 Yeah.

377
00:32:39,020 --> 00:32:39,340
 Right?

378
00:32:39,460 --> 00:32:52,700
 Like and so I feel like I take that term and it – as much as within our circles it has problematic connotations like Casey's metacognitive.

379
00:32:53,920 --> 00:32:57,160
 In students, they're like, okay, that's a thing, right?

380
00:32:57,260 --> 00:33:02,520
 That's like, okay, so I'm going to learn critical thinking skills in this science fiction class.

381
00:33:02,580 --> 00:33:03,900
 I'm not really going to learn science fiction.

382
00:33:04,100 --> 00:33:11,000
 At least that's the sense that I get from their responses, which is like this class is teaching me to think outside of the box.

383
00:33:11,060 --> 00:33:13,680
 That's another such a phrase, right?

384
00:33:13,680 --> 00:33:25,840
 So to me I feel like the calcification of that process into a term just becomes a hook, right?

385
00:33:25,840 --> 00:33:36,260
 Becomes a tactic that one can use in order to produce dispositional – and here's the thing to me that's important in all of that.

386
00:33:37,400 --> 00:33:40,480
 Is it like, Bubu, this didn't have to happen for you.

387
00:33:40,800 --> 00:33:46,420
 It wasn't – you know, you weren't necessarily going to go through the Hegel phase to get to the Deleuze phase.

388
00:33:46,660 --> 00:33:52,260
 If you'd asked me a year ago if Bubu was going to be really interested in reading Deleuze, I'd have been like probably not.

389
00:33:52,300 --> 00:33:54,400
 He's going to be reading Zizek, you know?

390
00:33:55,040 --> 00:33:59,440
 But it didn't go that way, right, for any number of possible reasons or whatever else.

391
00:33:59,440 --> 00:34:13,900
 So that there's no – there isn't a kind of causality – I mean going back to the very first aphorism – or rather the causality is subsequently assigned differently now that you're reading Deleuze – you know, now that you've become interested in Deleuze differently.

392
00:34:13,900 --> 00:34:31,540
 You want to talk about strange ripple effects, my buddy in the department texts me and says, thanks to you and your podcast, I have to now go read The Logic of Sense because my new honors student wants to write on The Logic of Sense and whatever, and she's been listening to your podcast.

393
00:34:32,060 --> 00:34:35,640
 And now you have to come out and buy me beers and explain The Logic of Sense to me.

394
00:34:36,820 --> 00:34:37,640
 Oh, my God.

395
00:34:37,640 --> 00:34:38,800
 That's so great.

396
00:34:39,120 --> 00:34:41,120
 One of the best texts I've ever gotten in my life.

397
00:34:41,900 --> 00:34:42,860
 That's great.

398
00:34:43,020 --> 00:34:43,780
 I love it.

399
00:34:43,900 --> 00:34:44,740
 I love it.

400
00:34:44,740 --> 00:34:48,140
 The impossible project of explaining The Logic of Sense.

401
00:34:53,380 --> 00:34:57,520
 Could I draw your attention to like 10-ish aphorisms here?

402
00:34:58,600 --> 00:35:13,000
 Just to sort of turn the conversation back to Nietzsche's perspectivalism and what's increasingly I'm seeing here is a sort of a non-human rhetoric in sort of –

403
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:24,960
 I think we've tried to do this several times is to sort of more explicitly connect the gay science to rhetoric from, you know, like we're rhetorical theorists.

404
00:35:24,960 --> 00:35:26,780
 It's like, well, how is this operating?

405
00:35:26,780 --> 00:35:41,740
 And so much of it has sort of like we've focused on, you know, rhetoric's capacity to sort of configure the world or to appropriate the world or to express and mutate from a certain perspective.

406
00:35:41,740 --> 00:35:54,640
 And I think that there's an interesting, more explicitly non-human way that this is sort of – you can read it, say, between 159 and 167.

407
00:35:55,260 --> 00:35:58,360
 So 159 – I'll read 159 and 160.

408
00:35:58,460 --> 00:35:59,120
 They're very short.

409
00:36:00,120 --> 00:36:02,160
 Every virtue has its age.

410
00:36:02,540 --> 00:36:07,060
 Whoever is unyielding these days will often have pains of conscience because of his candor.

411
00:36:07,220 --> 00:36:11,080
 For unyieldingness and candor are virtues that belong to a different age.

412
00:36:11,600 --> 00:36:14,880
 And here on 160, dealing with virtues.

413
00:36:15,300 --> 00:36:18,860
 To a virtue, too, one can be undignified and fawning.

414
00:36:19,460 --> 00:36:33,600
 And so much of this, especially right after that, talking about egoism, talking about the desire for rest, talking about victory and defeat, on talking about happiness, on being in one's own company, on misanthropy.

415
00:36:33,600 --> 00:36:56,920
 It is, in some ways, like imagining these virtues not as qualities that a person possesses, but as far more constitutive, evaluative points that take up and make and shape the world, not just the human being.

416
00:37:00,140 --> 00:37:18,460
 And I think that that's important – I think it's important that – because we will often talk about will – I mean, we're not, you know – but just like there is a lot of niche of like you've got to do something different or there is a sense of change something, do something different.

417
00:37:18,600 --> 00:37:22,140
 And it implies a sense of agency.

418
00:37:22,140 --> 00:37:22,840
 You have a will.

419
00:37:22,840 --> 00:37:26,100
 Right, like there would be sort of like this humanist sense of agency.

420
00:37:26,580 --> 00:37:34,580
 But then there are all those other places where it's very, very clear that that agency is comprised already of a multiplicity of wills.

421
00:37:34,840 --> 00:37:50,740
 I mean, that's, I guess, in part why it's not – like the will, the decision to exert agency is itself a symptom of a certain way of living in a certain decision-making circumstance.

422
00:37:50,740 --> 00:37:59,540
 Right, so that it's not simply a question of a humanist subject with the capacity to act, to decide, and they've got an array of decisions.

423
00:37:59,540 --> 00:38:20,260
 It is much more like each particular conglomeration of situation and subject are going to allow for different capacities of the subject to respond in those circumstances, which to me makes it less a humanist sense of agency and much more of this, I don't know, like amorphous vitalist sense.

424
00:38:20,420 --> 00:38:22,680
 Like this is life acting, not people.

425
00:38:23,080 --> 00:38:23,740
 Yeah, right.

426
00:38:23,940 --> 00:38:39,380
 Or is it – I would just say just because life has such as – one can imagine life as an organism here, but it's more like this is difference acting, which means it's always multiplicity or configurations of differential multiplicity.

427
00:38:39,380 --> 00:38:42,020
 That's a better way of saying it than life, yes.

428
00:38:42,340 --> 00:38:43,020
 I agree with you.

429
00:38:44,120 --> 00:38:54,820
 I mean, you could articulate that through almost all of his concepts too, like fostering or enabling the overman or enabling the eternal return.

430
00:38:55,140 --> 00:38:55,280
 Yeah.

431
00:38:55,500 --> 00:39:06,940
 These are all functions – not just of enabling agency, like you said, in the humanist sense, but rearticulating and reformulating agency as a product of context and contextual relations.

432
00:39:07,300 --> 00:39:07,640
 Right.

433
00:39:07,640 --> 00:39:13,740
 As opposed to dominating context, which I guess would just be one form of humanist subjectivity.

434
00:39:14,080 --> 00:39:15,820
 But it doesn't make it any less agency.

435
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:24,060
 I mean, that's the thing that has always appealed to me about Nietzsche is that you can use the humanist terminology still.

436
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:30,600
 It's not like let's just throw out – there's no agency and we are sort of subjects of social forces or something like that.

437
00:39:30,720 --> 00:39:32,220
 It's like, no, do something.

438
00:39:32,320 --> 00:39:33,120
 Do something different.

439
00:39:33,280 --> 00:39:36,720
 But not everybody is capable of doing something different in every particular encounter.

440
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:37,380
 Right.

441
00:39:37,380 --> 00:39:45,340
 Like, you know, you might come through from, you know, Boo Boo's progression, but it might go a different way.

442
00:39:45,420 --> 00:39:45,640
 Right.

443
00:39:45,720 --> 00:39:48,000
 That there is nothing, you know.

444
00:39:48,100 --> 00:39:53,800
 That's where it becomes – it becomes, for me, constantly this question of, I don't know, pedagogy.

445
00:39:53,960 --> 00:39:54,140
 Right.

446
00:39:54,240 --> 00:39:57,480
 Like, or education or learning.

447
00:39:57,600 --> 00:39:58,720
 I mean, what we were talking about earlier.

448
00:39:58,820 --> 00:40:04,780
 In fact, that's one of the ones that I really liked in here is 177.

449
00:40:05,160 --> 00:40:07,040
 Necessity of laughter for education.

450
00:40:07,300 --> 00:40:07,460
 Yeah.

451
00:40:07,460 --> 00:40:07,780
 Yeah.

452
00:40:08,140 --> 00:40:09,040
 Yeah, exactly.

453
00:40:09,280 --> 00:40:13,600
 And this is one – I think this is one that I take deeply to heart.

454
00:40:13,700 --> 00:40:13,900
 Yeah.

455
00:40:13,900 --> 00:40:20,980
 And I think that's one of the things that makes me a weirdo within the context that I circulate professionally.

456
00:40:21,240 --> 00:40:21,600
 Seriously.

457
00:40:21,820 --> 00:40:27,220
 It also makes you an object of critique as well.

458
00:40:27,420 --> 00:40:29,440
 You don't take yourself – you don't take it seriously.

459
00:40:29,660 --> 00:40:30,100
 Absolutely.

460
00:40:30,360 --> 00:40:31,180
 It's the exact opposite.

461
00:40:31,180 --> 00:40:32,800
 But, I mean, yeah.

462
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:41,000
 So, in Germany, higher men lack one great means of education, the laughter of higher men.

463
00:40:41,220 --> 00:40:43,360
 For in Germany, they don't laugh.

464
00:40:44,120 --> 00:40:44,300
 Right?

465
00:40:44,500 --> 00:40:51,980
 In other words – so, just to take that, like, the laughter of higher men is a means of education.

466
00:40:52,720 --> 00:40:53,140
 Mm-hmm.

467
00:40:53,600 --> 00:40:53,920
 Right?

468
00:40:54,280 --> 00:40:56,700
 And that, to me, is really interesting.

469
00:40:57,360 --> 00:40:58,800
 I mean, who says that?

470
00:40:59,040 --> 00:40:59,200
 Yeah.

471
00:40:59,240 --> 00:40:59,380
 Right?

472
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:03,120
 Who says, like, okay, learning how to laugh.

473
00:41:03,500 --> 00:41:03,720
 Yeah.

474
00:41:03,980 --> 00:41:08,140
 Or learning from the laughter of others.

475
00:41:09,280 --> 00:41:10,940
 Not simply as derision.

476
00:41:11,660 --> 00:41:11,780
 Right?

477
00:41:11,780 --> 00:41:13,600
 So, that's the important part.

478
00:41:13,680 --> 00:41:16,600
 Because now go to aphorism 200 on laughter.

479
00:41:17,300 --> 00:41:19,140
 Laughter means to gloat.

480
00:41:19,520 --> 00:41:21,440
 But with a good conscience.

481
00:41:21,740 --> 00:41:22,240
 Good conscience.

482
00:41:22,580 --> 00:41:22,800
 Right.

483
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:23,220
 Right.

484
00:41:23,360 --> 00:41:23,840
 Exactly.

485
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:25,720
 It obviously changes everything.

486
00:41:25,880 --> 00:41:32,100
 And especially because I think, you know, 186, bad conscience, everything he does now is upright and orderly.

487
00:41:32,200 --> 00:41:33,860
 And still he has bad conscience.

488
00:41:34,180 --> 00:41:36,160
 For the extraordinary is his task.

489
00:41:38,980 --> 00:41:40,180
 That's cool stuff.

490
00:41:40,340 --> 00:41:41,000
 I mean, it is.

491
00:41:41,120 --> 00:41:46,040
 It's like – to me, it's like this is just – this is a book on pedagogy.

492
00:41:46,680 --> 00:41:51,860
 And here, I mean, I think what I like about laughter here so much is it's not – go back to the agents thing.

493
00:41:51,860 --> 00:41:53,360
 It's not that I decide to laugh.

494
00:41:53,360 --> 00:41:55,700
 It's not that I decide to laugh and now I'm going to master the art of laughing.

495
00:41:55,700 --> 00:41:56,280
 I was going to say that.

496
00:41:56,280 --> 00:41:58,980
 It's to be taken up in the flow of laughter.

497
00:41:58,980 --> 00:42:01,020
 That is not simply mine.

498
00:42:01,020 --> 00:42:01,160
 Right.

499
00:42:01,160 --> 00:42:03,340
 A certain sort of cosmic comedy.

500
00:42:03,600 --> 00:42:07,580
 You know, this 153 is like, from where shall I take this tragic solution?

501
00:42:07,740 --> 00:42:09,740
 Should I start considering a comic solution?

502
00:42:09,960 --> 00:42:10,980
 The comic solution.

503
00:42:11,120 --> 00:42:11,280
 Yeah.

504
00:42:11,400 --> 00:42:12,520
 Move from tragedy to comedy.

505
00:42:12,740 --> 00:42:15,640
 And that's the beginning of the pithy aphorisms section, right?

506
00:42:16,040 --> 00:42:22,760
 I mean, there has to be something there to the notion that, like you're saying, laughter is somewhat involuntary, right?

507
00:42:22,800 --> 00:42:26,960
 It's like interruption as opposed to – like you don't choose to laugh unless you do.

508
00:42:27,380 --> 00:42:32,600
 But like you also think about people who don't laugh as models for like what not to be.

509
00:42:32,800 --> 00:42:34,260
 Like Trump, you'll never see him laugh.

510
00:42:34,720 --> 00:42:41,400
 But also like we also take it as signs of wisdom or self-control or other things, right?

511
00:42:41,400 --> 00:42:59,440
 And there's – here there's – insofar as it feels like if I'm exerting or if I'm doing anything in my capacity to laugh, it's a practiced willingness or ability to be given over, to be taken up by the thing.

512
00:42:59,640 --> 00:43:03,580
 I mean, look, guys, the title of the book, right?

513
00:43:03,820 --> 00:43:05,340
 Freudic Wiesenschaft, right?

514
00:43:05,460 --> 00:43:09,300
 So it's joyful or gay, you know, learning, wisdom, whatever.

515
00:43:09,640 --> 00:43:12,060
 Like, I mean, that's – it is.

516
00:43:12,160 --> 00:43:20,120
 I feel like in most cases where you know you're in a learning environment, it's serious.

517
00:43:21,560 --> 00:43:29,580
 And there is a – there is an air of earnest, earnestness about it.

518
00:43:29,840 --> 00:43:37,320
 And this is to me the huge lesson of Nietzsche is like fuck those fuckers, you know?

519
00:43:37,500 --> 00:43:39,320
 Like that's not the only way.

520
00:43:39,460 --> 00:43:42,080
 Like that's just – that's not the only style, right?

521
00:43:42,080 --> 00:43:43,820
 That one can laugh at this.

522
00:43:44,040 --> 00:43:46,180
 And again, not just – not derisively.

523
00:43:46,340 --> 00:43:48,780
 It's schadenfreude but with a good conscience, right?

524
00:43:48,780 --> 00:43:51,300
 Like, oh, wow, it sucks to be them.

525
00:43:52,660 --> 00:43:55,380
 But also to be taken – yeah, to be taken through it.

526
00:43:55,780 --> 00:43:56,180
 Yeah.

527
00:43:57,260 --> 00:44:03,140
 Well, allowing yourself to be vulnerable to otherness or to – or however you want to term it.

528
00:44:03,280 --> 00:44:09,400
 I think that's something that I've reflected on as a process of my own writing that I think it's always been there.

529
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:21,700
 But recently that's what's been giving me joy in the writing process is when you try to make a – when you try to consolidate a concept, which is kind of inevitable, you try to delineate a concept, put something in a box.

530
00:44:21,960 --> 00:44:23,140
 And then you realize it doesn't fit.

531
00:44:23,660 --> 00:44:26,860
 And then you try to shape it around and see if it fits in another context.

532
00:44:26,900 --> 00:44:27,400
 And it doesn't.

533
00:44:27,760 --> 00:44:31,900
 And then there's never an ultimate container for whatever you're trying to accomplish.

534
00:44:32,220 --> 00:44:37,780
 But that movement of dwelling in that indeterminacy, that's the joy of it.

535
00:44:37,780 --> 00:44:55,460
 But that really gets me thinking, Nate, in terms of that openness to the other because that's such a trope of a certain kind of left-leaning theory that is so incredibly – I think this is also in many ways a left-leaning theory or oftentimes left-friendly theory.

536
00:44:55,460 --> 00:45:19,540
 But there's such a – there's an important pivot there on that what kind of practiced openness to the other is being cultivated because the way that it so often gets rendered as a sort of undifferentiated openness, an openness without laughter, an openness of say like the camel, the desire to bear the otherness of the person,

537
00:45:19,540 --> 00:45:25,560
 to respect it, to affirm it, to recognize it, to whatever it is.

538
00:45:25,780 --> 00:45:31,560
 And then all of that then sort of gets laid through a certain sense of authenticity.

539
00:45:31,560 --> 00:45:33,040
 Am I being transparent?

540
00:45:33,340 --> 00:45:34,460
 Am I colonizing it?

541
00:45:34,480 --> 00:45:35,600
 Am I appropriating it?

542
00:45:35,600 --> 00:45:37,780
 Am I allowing it to shine through?

543
00:45:38,780 --> 00:45:47,160
 And then, you know, like then one's actions, one's appropriations become the condemnable thing, the damnable thing.

544
00:45:47,160 --> 00:45:56,260
 The – it becomes its own kind of nihilism to erase, to efface the self in the face of the difference of the other, to bear it, to recognize it.

545
00:45:56,760 --> 00:46:08,440
 And, you know, I think of those – the three metamorphoses in Zarathustra and from the camel who I think is part of that Kant joke that you were talking about,

546
00:46:08,440 --> 00:46:16,820
 with like all of Kant as being, you know, the camel of the people, to the lion, the critic, but to the child.

547
00:46:16,820 --> 00:46:30,220
 And think about the laughter of the child is the – it has to be that openness to the other, that practice vulnerability to the other is transformative of other and self.

548
00:46:31,100 --> 00:46:43,540
 It's not – it's not an undifferentiated portal or opening wherein the integrity of the essence of the other is simply transported to me without intervention.

549
00:46:43,760 --> 00:46:43,960
 Right.

550
00:46:44,300 --> 00:46:48,600
 It's not separate from the mechanism of conceptuality or cognition.

551
00:46:48,880 --> 00:46:49,840
 It's part of it.

552
00:46:50,060 --> 00:46:56,960
 So it's like even if you're valuing or preferencing or what's the word?

553
00:46:57,080 --> 00:47:05,980
 Like sort of – even if you're emphasizing that vulnerability to otherness, at least under Hegel's thinking or at least under my sort of quasi-Hegelian thinking,

554
00:47:06,500 --> 00:47:08,960
 you also have that cutting motion, right?

555
00:47:09,060 --> 00:47:13,380
 Like it's always a de-territorialization and a territorialization, right?

556
00:47:13,380 --> 00:47:14,800
 The simultaneity of that.

557
00:47:14,800 --> 00:47:23,780
 I find so much – I find so much alterity ethics to whether it – even when it tries to circumvent it, to begin with I and other, right?

558
00:47:23,880 --> 00:47:33,080
 Even when it's sort of like, you know, the you is this constitutive element of the I, it's still then sort of like rush over that.

559
00:47:33,400 --> 00:47:37,700
 And then now it's just about I and other and the capacity of violence between the two.

560
00:47:38,620 --> 00:47:49,320
 And that – like that just sets up, I think, a politics and an ethics of – well, they're just not really good outcomes to it other than self-annihilation.

561
00:47:50,540 --> 00:47:50,940
 Yeah.

562
00:47:51,300 --> 00:47:58,960
 And then it – a lot of it seems to be just fetishizing that indeterminacy in a kind of unproductive way too.

563
00:47:58,960 --> 00:48:03,840
 Where it's just like you don't really get anything out of that particular orientation.

564
00:48:04,160 --> 00:48:04,840
 At least I don't.

565
00:48:04,940 --> 00:48:09,020
 Except for the interminable, you know, quagmire of it.

566
00:48:10,280 --> 00:48:10,540
 Yeah.

567
00:48:10,900 --> 00:48:11,300
 Yeah.

568
00:48:11,420 --> 00:48:12,640
 I'm going to cheat.

569
00:48:13,160 --> 00:48:18,740
 I had to go to my old – the old version that has my notes that I've been reading for 20 years.

570
00:48:19,040 --> 00:48:20,120
 Because I couldn't find it.

571
00:48:20,120 --> 00:48:20,260
 Oh, boy.

572
00:48:20,260 --> 00:48:23,180
 And I'm cheating because I'm jumping into book four.

573
00:48:23,360 --> 00:48:26,700
 But it just, I think, really fits with what we're talking about here.

574
00:48:26,800 --> 00:48:31,000
 And it's aphorism number 324 in Media Vita.

575
00:48:32,560 --> 00:48:36,760
 And it is – I'll just read the first brief part.

576
00:48:36,760 --> 00:48:39,020
 No, life has not disappointed me.

577
00:48:39,120 --> 00:48:43,120
 On the contrary, I find it truer, more desirable, and mysterious every year.

578
00:48:43,500 --> 00:48:52,180
 Ever since the day when the great liberator came to me, the idea that life could be an experiment of the seeker for knowledge.

579
00:48:52,180 --> 00:48:55,700
 And not a duty, not a calamity, not a trickery.

580
00:48:56,140 --> 00:49:03,340
 And knowledge itself, let it be something else for others, for example, a bed to rest on, or the way to such a bed, a diversion, a form of leisure.

581
00:49:03,740 --> 00:49:09,340
 For me, it is a world of dangers and victories in which heroic feelings, too, find places to dance and play.

582
00:49:09,820 --> 00:49:11,360
 Life as a means to knowledge.

583
00:49:11,480 --> 00:49:16,700
 With this principle in one's heart, one can live not only boldly but even gaily, and laugh gaily, too.

584
00:49:16,700 --> 00:49:22,600
 And who knows how to laugh anyway and live well if he does not first know a good deal about war and victory.

585
00:49:23,120 --> 00:49:36,340
 So, I mean, this is to me that – that's that tone of like, hey, what happens if you start thinking that thinking is itself an action that life offers, right?

586
00:49:36,340 --> 00:49:45,060
 And not as something to understand or to comprehend or to – but as an experiment and as a risky –

587
00:49:45,060 --> 00:49:45,860
 As an intervention.

588
00:49:46,100 --> 00:49:52,860
 Like what you guys are talking about, the genuinely risky experiment where sense of self and identity and things like this,

589
00:49:52,960 --> 00:49:54,900
 These are all going to be at stake.

590
00:49:54,960 --> 00:49:58,180
 And it's like, oh, wow, that's the cool part.

591
00:49:58,580 --> 00:50:00,740
 That's not the thing that you want to –

592
00:50:00,740 --> 00:50:01,420
 Forstall.

593
00:50:01,540 --> 00:50:02,220
 Stiff arm.

594
00:50:02,520 --> 00:50:03,480
 Yeah, at all.

595
00:50:03,660 --> 00:50:04,900
 Like that's the thing.

596
00:50:04,900 --> 00:50:11,840
 I mean, what a different ethos one has to learning in that sense to me.

597
00:50:12,100 --> 00:50:22,800
 And that's why I continually return to Nietzsche despite all of the – I reckon, you know, many problems and the many very smart people I know who are like, yeah, Nietzsche is this, that, you know.

598
00:50:22,800 --> 00:50:26,300
 And I'm just like, yeah, but he fucking laughs, you know.

599
00:50:26,300 --> 00:50:33,200
 Or he teaches us laughter as a way of living and thinking, right?

600
00:50:33,320 --> 00:50:39,960
 So the idea of – in that sense, it's like Deleuze makes a lot, and I think rightfully so, of the tragic, right?

601
00:50:39,960 --> 00:50:41,700
 Like the role of the tragic in Nietzsche.

602
00:50:41,920 --> 00:50:46,980
 But like there's something else there that's not simply – we couldn't simply call it the comic.

603
00:50:47,140 --> 00:50:51,420
 It's not just the comic as the other of the tragic, you know.

604
00:50:52,080 --> 00:51:01,820
 And that's to me like – that's the style thing that I feel like – Nietzsche offers that, frankly, I don't get anywhere.

605
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:08,680
 I mean, Deleuze is the next closest thing to me, you know, of like let's have fun and make stuff.

606
00:51:08,820 --> 00:51:14,300
 I mean, I know that sounds so stupid when I say it like that, you know.

607
00:51:15,260 --> 00:51:18,520
 But – and it's risky because it's not a kid's, you know.

608
00:51:18,860 --> 00:51:30,500
 But think about the kind – when we're talking about laughter and joy here, think about the kind of desire that it presupposes.

609
00:51:30,500 --> 00:51:35,480
 Because it does not presuppose a desire that – organized around lack.

610
00:51:35,560 --> 00:51:37,460
 It is not a satiating.

611
00:51:37,760 --> 00:51:47,560
 It is not – it is – yeah, it is not an amelioration of a prior wound or, you know, the cessation of some kind of suffering or hurting.

612
00:51:47,560 --> 00:52:02,620
 It is the joy or the feeling of – it is simultaneously a pain and a joy of a rupturing or a bursting forth of a –

613
00:52:02,620 --> 00:52:12,460
 Well, it's just – it's like what Boo Boo was just describing a moment ago in terms of his own thinking, right, where like you try to contextualize it and it fails.

614
00:52:12,460 --> 00:52:17,280
 So there's a number of affective dispositions, you know, you can be like, fuck, I didn't get it.

615
00:52:17,320 --> 00:52:18,220
 Well, let me try it again.

616
00:52:18,380 --> 00:52:19,180
 Fuck, I didn't get it.

617
00:52:19,220 --> 00:52:20,580
 Like, you know, and we all know.

618
00:52:20,660 --> 00:52:22,520
 We all work like that sometimes, right?

619
00:52:22,540 --> 00:52:25,980
 Like that's not really right and let me try something else and that's not really right.

620
00:52:25,980 --> 00:52:41,800
 But the, you know, the move that you suggested there, Boo Boo, is to realize that, oh, it's the – it's the making of the series, the serial production of potential context and efforts to enclose that is the actual work, not the enclosure itself, right?

621
00:52:41,880 --> 00:52:44,820
 And so that's the point where you go, oh, life is an experiment.

622
00:52:45,140 --> 00:52:46,680
 Oh, thinking is an experiment.

623
00:52:46,980 --> 00:52:51,960
 Oh, it's not about trying to understand in the sense of finally – like I finally got it.

624
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:53,860
 I got my line on this aphorism.

625
00:52:53,860 --> 00:52:58,880
 I've got the thing that I know about whatever the thinker is and now I can move on.

626
00:52:59,020 --> 00:53:03,180
 It's always about that sort of serial production of recontextualizations.

627
00:53:07,660 --> 00:53:11,080
 I was talking to my students about this the other day.

628
00:53:11,240 --> 00:53:20,240
 Like, do you know like an asymptotic relation where – like I guess in math, like you're getting closer and – like say this line is reality.

629
00:53:20,240 --> 00:53:21,040
 You never touch law of limits.

630
00:53:21,040 --> 00:53:24,020
 And yeah, and you're just getting closer and closer to reality.

631
00:53:24,220 --> 00:53:38,600
 So like if you're trying to – in psychoanalysis, there's this notion that if you specify your language about your own emotions, so instead of you just happy and sad, let's say you're grateful to be around your family.

632
00:53:38,820 --> 00:53:47,140
 So like you're getting more specific about your emotional intelligence and then that's supposed to lead to like better mental health.

633
00:53:47,620 --> 00:53:55,100
 But that logic is that if you get better at specifying your emotions, you're getting closer to the reality of your emotions.

634
00:53:55,100 --> 00:54:02,580
 When really, they're just always – like language and emotionality are always kind of both distant and the same thing.

635
00:54:02,760 --> 00:54:10,200
 Like there's not – the more facility you gain, the more sort of reality that you see that is simply an artifice that fails to get there.

636
00:54:10,280 --> 00:54:13,160
 So there's like a pain that coincides with the facility.

637
00:54:13,160 --> 00:54:33,020
 What happens when you think about say like the complication, nuance facility with language as only ever series of interventions that can't help but always intersect, that never correspond, never reflect, never true, false, go out the window.

638
00:54:33,580 --> 00:54:39,800
 But, you know, as – again, as points of intervention, never possible of failing.

639
00:54:40,800 --> 00:54:41,280
 Right.

640
00:54:41,440 --> 00:54:43,240
 It would just be like John's thing.

641
00:54:43,340 --> 00:54:45,560
 It's just different styles of engagement.

642
00:54:45,700 --> 00:54:48,620
 To say you're happy and to say you're – to specify it.

643
00:54:48,880 --> 00:54:52,260
 I mean those are not like – it wouldn't be a depth model.

644
00:54:52,560 --> 00:54:55,440
 It's just a different orientation towards your own emotional stages.

645
00:54:55,440 --> 00:54:57,000
 One wouldn't be truer than the other.

646
00:54:57,140 --> 00:55:00,220
 But they would have different modulations of intervention.

647
00:55:01,200 --> 00:55:01,740
 Of course.

648
00:55:02,080 --> 00:55:02,340
 Yeah.

649
00:55:02,760 --> 00:55:09,920
 But you wouldn't be – yeah, you wouldn't be progressively narrowing and contextualizing to the point of reaching the reality.

650
00:55:09,920 --> 00:55:20,940
 But see, but that's the thing is – so – but you're like – what that second version is is the joy of thinking and creating increased specification.

651
00:55:21,380 --> 00:55:21,540
 Yeah.

652
00:55:21,780 --> 00:55:27,600
 Not because it's getting closer to a point but because of the joy of creating specification.

653
00:55:28,180 --> 00:55:28,300
 Right.

654
00:55:28,460 --> 00:55:29,140
 Like –

655
00:55:29,140 --> 00:55:29,840
 And they're also just –

656
00:55:29,840 --> 00:55:31,220
 The experiment of thinking.

657
00:55:31,400 --> 00:55:44,200
 You know, like it's – it's also – what are the – one's facility with the thing allows for more joy, allows for a greater surface area of affecting and being affected by others.

658
00:55:44,200 --> 00:55:51,460
 So, like one can still say, like, yeah, you know, cultivate a capacity to talk about emotions beyond happy, sad.

659
00:55:51,900 --> 00:55:53,440
 Yeah, do that.

660
00:55:53,520 --> 00:56:01,980
 But not because it more accurately reflects a depth or, you know, an underlying being.

661
00:56:02,220 --> 00:56:08,000
 But because it creates more opportunities or more points of contact for experimentation.

662
00:56:08,420 --> 00:56:08,560
 Yeah.

663
00:56:08,560 --> 00:56:09,520
 For that joy.

664
00:56:10,580 --> 00:56:10,900
 Right.

665
00:56:10,960 --> 00:56:15,120
 It's just not operating by a logic of truth, true and false, or depth.

666
00:56:15,460 --> 00:56:18,740
 Like you're not – specificity is not on the way to truth.

667
00:56:19,320 --> 00:56:19,420
 Right.

668
00:56:19,420 --> 00:56:20,280
 It's just –

669
00:56:20,280 --> 00:56:21,920
 Yeah, again, a different valence.

670
00:56:22,140 --> 00:56:24,280
 But you almost have to think about it in a physical register.

671
00:56:24,420 --> 00:56:37,800
 It's like when you're nuancing your language with something, you're just creating more points of contact, greater surface area, more modes of intervention or experimentation, none of which are predetermined to produce X, Y, or Z.

672
00:56:37,960 --> 00:56:41,580
 But, you know, more tends to lead to more.

673
00:56:42,800 --> 00:56:43,020
 Yeah.

674
00:56:43,340 --> 00:56:43,720
 Yeah.

675
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:47,140
 But I just – yeah, we were having this conversation in class.

676
00:56:47,140 --> 00:56:54,240
 And I guess I was just thinking like – because people – even in my own writing, you tend to think complexity equals truth.

677
00:56:54,460 --> 00:57:01,260
 But it's just – again, it's just a phase shift in your approach toward a problematic.

678
00:57:02,060 --> 00:57:04,160
 It's not like a rival.

679
00:57:04,480 --> 00:57:04,700
 Yeah.

680
00:57:04,860 --> 00:57:05,800
 Yeah, at something.

681
00:57:06,220 --> 00:57:06,280
 Yeah.

682
00:57:06,280 --> 00:57:14,040
 But I do think that there is something – I do want to – like when you initially said this, Nathaniel, I was skeptical where you said it's increasing a surface area.

683
00:57:14,040 --> 00:57:16,620
 And I'm like, well, it would just be different rather than increasing.

684
00:57:17,140 --> 00:57:18,980
 But then I think that you might be right.

685
00:57:19,080 --> 00:57:21,980
 Like I think that it is actually increasing surface area.

686
00:57:21,980 --> 00:57:44,800
 Like I think that there is a way in which what that specificity – the desire to get it right produces a way of interacting which enables some – which enables something that's just not available if you're not concerned with getting it right.

687
00:57:45,080 --> 00:57:52,860
 So there's that sense in which the true and the false is in the service of increasing surface area.

688
00:57:52,860 --> 00:57:53,000
 Yeah.

689
00:57:54,680 --> 00:58:01,020
 Even though we all think the purpose of true and false is to reduce surface area by delineating.

690
00:58:01,140 --> 00:58:01,640
 Right?

691
00:58:01,640 --> 00:58:01,840
 Yeah.

692
00:58:02,520 --> 00:58:02,660
 Yeah.

693
00:58:03,340 --> 00:58:11,340
 It becomes one more mechanism by which – or it becomes one more mechanism by which of producing the nuance of producing – yeah, I agree.

694
00:58:11,560 --> 00:58:11,960
 Right.

695
00:58:12,620 --> 00:58:21,440
 Well, so then the kind of more – what you'd normally think of as a traditional scientific approach is still generative of complexity.

696
00:58:21,800 --> 00:58:21,820
 Yeah.

697
00:58:21,820 --> 00:58:24,160
 And in fact, it's extremely generative.

698
00:58:24,340 --> 00:58:24,360
 Right.

699
00:58:24,360 --> 00:58:24,840
 Of course.

700
00:58:25,120 --> 00:58:25,560
 Of course.

701
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:26,220
 Yeah.

702
00:58:26,820 --> 00:58:32,140
 But so would you – like it's not a critique then of that dynamic.

703
00:58:32,280 --> 00:58:33,780
 It's just a diagnosis.

704
00:58:34,180 --> 00:58:45,100
 The asymptotic is just – the asymptotic is not – the asymptotic is a symptom in a different – in Nathaniel's diagram of words and things that goes – that does that weird thing.

705
00:58:45,100 --> 00:58:47,380
 Like the asymptotic is a diagram.

706
00:58:48,220 --> 00:58:50,060
 It's just not the diagram.

707
00:58:50,420 --> 00:58:51,740
 It's just a part of.

708
00:58:52,120 --> 00:58:53,240
 But it's a tool.

709
00:58:53,260 --> 00:58:55,500
 It's a style of intervention that presumes itself –

710
00:58:55,500 --> 00:58:56,220
 Be more precise.

711
00:58:56,440 --> 00:58:57,760
 Be more – like be more precise.

712
00:58:57,880 --> 00:59:03,620
 Like I always think of it – you know, I never use the terminology of clarity in my writing classes.

713
00:59:03,740 --> 00:59:11,800
 I always use the terminology of precision because it is a question of cutting and, you know, delineating this thing from that thing.

714
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:17,040
 And not to get it right necessarily but to create more available responses.

715
00:59:17,320 --> 00:59:17,360
 Yeah.

716
00:59:17,560 --> 00:59:17,660
 Yeah.

717
00:59:17,860 --> 00:59:18,240
 You know?

718
00:59:18,400 --> 00:59:26,180
 So if you just simply stick with happy and sad, you have fewer possible emotional states.

719
00:59:26,960 --> 00:59:27,080
 Yeah.

720
00:59:27,400 --> 00:59:28,160
 I mean they're –

721
00:59:28,160 --> 00:59:32,120
 We have as many emotional states as we have languages to produce them.

722
00:59:32,920 --> 00:59:33,140
 Yeah.

723
00:59:33,200 --> 00:59:33,420
 Right?

724
00:59:33,500 --> 00:59:33,640
 Yeah.

725
00:59:33,960 --> 00:59:36,360
 Although it's not the language that it produces, right?

726
00:59:36,420 --> 00:59:40,440
 Like so it's – we can't simply say, ah, it's a terminological thing.

727
00:59:40,440 --> 00:59:46,620
 The shift is just really quickly and I think it's pretty much on the same – in the same vein here.

728
00:59:46,720 --> 00:59:52,520
 But here's a word that gets stuck with me every once in a while and especially the etymology of it.

729
00:59:52,600 --> 01:00:04,060
 And it's sort of – the word suffer and especially through the sort of the phrase, I don't suffer fools, which always, you know, for a long time struck me as a strange way of using the word suffer.

730
01:00:05,060 --> 01:00:17,140
 Until, you know, you start diving into the etymology a little bit more and thinking of suffer as a – in the more generic sense as to experience or to undergo or to have –

731
01:00:17,140 --> 01:00:17,140
 Endure.

732
01:00:17,140 --> 01:00:17,660
 To develop –

733
01:00:17,660 --> 01:00:18,220
 To endure.

734
01:00:18,380 --> 01:00:20,480
 To have our kind of – yes, be subjected to.

735
01:00:21,260 --> 01:00:26,680
 And this is less about recovering a real, more authentic notion of suffer.

736
01:00:27,620 --> 01:00:39,960
 Although I think it is helpful to think of that etymology, say, like when Nietzsche talks about perceiving life as suffering and the Greeks of thinking life as suffering because it's a very different sense of suffering that I think that he's getting after there.

737
01:00:39,960 --> 01:00:43,560
 But it's more the trajectory of the etymology itself.

738
01:00:43,980 --> 01:00:55,200
 Like what does it tell us that that sense of suffering condenses itself into pain and suffering and the unpleasantness of life?

739
01:00:55,200 --> 01:01:18,820
 It just – and it really – it always comes to me the most strongly when I'm reading Nietzsche on Christianity or Nietzsche or like even that phrase that you just read from book four about thinking as a bed to rest on, as a forestallment, as a prevention of the suffering.

740
01:01:18,820 --> 01:01:33,620
 Like the – it's – to me that the trajectory of that etymology is Christian in so far as it condemns the world and suffering life as something that is evil and sinful that needs to be redeemed.

741
01:01:33,620 --> 01:01:54,200
 But then also it speaks to a consistent labor and effort and something I think generally but also we could just say sum it up with the term modernity or certainly like a technological orientation to modernity to – that sees our collective telos as reducing suffering.

742
01:01:54,200 --> 01:01:59,840
 Which is to reduce those points of contact, to reduce that – to reduce exposure.

743
01:01:59,840 --> 01:02:01,140
 To reduce exposure, right?

744
01:02:01,140 --> 01:02:08,240
 Because that's the sense in which like I've always thought the cogito, the dream of the cogito is like a fucking bubble boy, right?

745
01:02:08,240 --> 01:02:08,300
 Yeah.

746
01:02:08,360 --> 01:02:19,800
 Like I mean it's like let's have no outside – let's have no contact with the outside is the sort of like platonic to Cartesian ideal of subjectivity.

747
01:02:20,140 --> 01:02:20,340
 Yeah.

748
01:02:20,340 --> 01:02:26,840
 You know, and so anything that one is subject to is suffering in both senses, right?

749
01:02:26,900 --> 01:02:40,560
 It's just – it is an intrusion, an incursion, which doesn't have to – I mean that just means that to live is to suffer in the negative –

750
01:02:40,560 --> 01:02:41,440
 In the negative sense.

751
01:02:41,440 --> 01:02:42,400
 The common sense of negative sense.

752
01:02:42,400 --> 01:02:48,060
 Get through it with as little – with as little like violation as possible.

753
01:02:48,060 --> 01:02:51,880
 And I have to say like I live like that so much, right?

754
01:02:51,940 --> 01:03:10,040
 Like I feel like in my own sort of emotional disposition towards like I find myself so much living in a kind of endurance, a camel mode of like get through it, get through this class, get through this semester, get through the situate, you know, like get through, get through.

755
01:03:11,120 --> 01:03:17,940
 And those occasional times where you're like, oh, there's something other than getting through that's available here.

756
01:03:17,940 --> 01:03:18,240
 Yeah.

757
01:03:18,240 --> 01:03:24,900
 There's something other than endurance that's available here that lightens – I mean that's what, you know, what I need Nietzsche for.

758
01:03:25,100 --> 01:03:25,300
 Yeah.

759
01:03:25,300 --> 01:03:29,880
 To give me that – to teach me that laughter, you know.

760
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:52,320
 That connection, though, to the Kogito just lit a huge light bulb for me, though, is thinking about the notion of the sovereign individual and in that sort of lineage of the sovereign of the Kogito as a fortress unto oneself that is able to demarcate self from other and keep the other at bay.

761
01:03:52,740 --> 01:04:01,340
 Think about the sense of the sovereign that Nietzsche articulates at the beginning of book two of on genealogy of morality.

762
01:04:01,620 --> 01:04:02,260
 Genealogy of morals.

763
01:04:02,480 --> 01:04:03,540
 Of morals.

764
01:04:04,080 --> 01:04:09,000
 And here the sense of the sovereign is marked by their capacity to promise.

765
01:04:11,160 --> 01:04:26,720
 And it's a very interesting kind of consistency that is required by the sovereign in order to promise because there has to be a force of will that is able to carve oneself out to promise.

766
01:04:26,720 --> 01:04:27,380
 Predict the future.

767
01:04:27,620 --> 01:04:29,440
 Yeah, predict the future effectively.

768
01:04:29,940 --> 01:04:33,460
 But not just predict the future, to make the future in such a way.

769
01:04:33,460 --> 01:04:35,660
 Make the future happen the way that I say it's going to be.

770
01:04:35,660 --> 01:04:36,260
 That is going to happen.

771
01:04:36,260 --> 01:04:37,720
 I will be there at five o'clock.

772
01:04:37,720 --> 01:04:40,280
 Which means I'm going to, yes, not a predicting of the future.

773
01:04:40,360 --> 01:04:42,340
 I'm going to make the future like this.

774
01:04:42,480 --> 01:04:48,640
 And now think about the kind of exposure that that sovereign has to have to the world around them.

775
01:04:48,780 --> 01:04:52,380
 This cannot be bubble wrapping self-autonomy.

776
01:04:52,780 --> 01:05:03,820
 This has to be, and I will transform myself in a relationship to the world, to the other, in such a way that whatever else happens to me, I will be there at five o'clock.

777
01:05:03,960 --> 01:05:05,140
 I'll be there at five o'clock.

778
01:05:05,140 --> 01:05:07,540
 It'll be a different me maybe, but I'll be there.

779
01:05:08,620 --> 01:05:08,740
 Yeah.

780
01:05:09,800 --> 01:05:10,960
 That's a difference in the song.

781
01:05:10,960 --> 01:05:13,640
 But I will almost always, I always experience it.

782
01:05:13,680 --> 01:05:17,240
 I mean, for me, I mostly experience it as like an imposition.

783
01:05:17,420 --> 01:05:19,860
 Like, fuck, now I've got to control the world.

784
01:05:20,340 --> 01:05:20,440
 Yeah.

785
01:05:20,520 --> 01:05:23,500
 You know, now I've got to make this thing happen at five o'clock.

786
01:05:23,600 --> 01:05:29,080
 And even though, even if it's something that I might even enjoy, like I went to see a play last Friday night.

787
01:05:29,200 --> 01:05:34,220
 And the whole, all day long, I was like, oh, fuck, I've got to do that at six o'clock.

788
01:05:34,220 --> 01:05:36,700
 And I'm just going to a goddamn play, right?

789
01:05:36,860 --> 01:05:39,280
 Like, I mean, it's Sweeney Todd, the musical.

790
01:05:39,460 --> 01:05:41,080
 I mean, maybe that was part of it, but, you know.

791
01:05:41,520 --> 01:05:45,400
 But the whole day, I'm just like, oh, man, I'm going to have to do it.

792
01:05:45,400 --> 01:05:46,760
 Like, it's like an obligation.

793
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:59,860
 And I know, I mean, I know like how lousy of a way that is to live, but I see that sense of like, oh, I got to go to Sweeney Todd on Friday night with, you know.

794
01:06:00,220 --> 01:06:13,100
 And just being, trying to figure out how to like, how to turn, how to turn your lenses so that it's like, I get to rather than I'm obligated to, you know.

795
01:06:13,100 --> 01:06:22,240
 But with the relationship to the promise, so it's one thing to, say, make Sweeney Todd or the time spent with John as the object of affirmation.

796
01:06:22,580 --> 01:06:25,700
 What happens when it's the promise that is the object of affirmation?

797
01:06:28,180 --> 01:06:38,400
 Meaning that the promise, the commitment to make the future becomes a differential to affirm and to take joy in.

798
01:06:38,420 --> 01:06:38,640
 Right.

799
01:06:38,720 --> 01:06:39,800
 Rather than an obligation.

800
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:41,060
 Rather than an obligation.

801
01:06:41,320 --> 01:06:43,680
 Rather than something to fuck up or not fuck up.

802
01:06:43,820 --> 01:06:48,260
 Rather than something to err or sin against or commit.

803
01:06:48,720 --> 01:06:52,240
 Because now think about the good, bad, good, evil relationship.

804
01:06:52,240 --> 01:06:58,780
 As soon as that promise has been set, everything, from a certain perspective, everything is negatively related to it.

805
01:06:58,840 --> 01:07:02,920
 It becomes an entity that can be violated, that can be transgressed against.

806
01:07:03,260 --> 01:07:09,740
 What happens if it comes from the, rather than the good, evil perspective, but from the good, bad perspective?

807
01:07:10,240 --> 01:07:15,360
 It is an affirm, it is an expression of my, of will.

808
01:07:15,360 --> 01:07:19,880
 It is an expression of delight and a self-transforming expression of delight.

809
01:07:20,760 --> 01:07:21,200
 Yeah.

810
01:07:21,380 --> 01:07:21,680
 Right.

811
01:07:21,880 --> 01:07:25,540
 That's why I like, there was that aphorism in there of, like, someone who compliments you.

812
01:07:25,840 --> 01:07:26,140
 Yeah.

813
01:07:26,480 --> 01:07:27,180
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

814
01:07:27,340 --> 01:07:29,400
 Makes themselves your equal.

815
01:07:29,780 --> 01:07:30,220
 Yes.

816
01:07:30,300 --> 01:07:32,120
 And I'm like, I love that.

817
01:07:32,200 --> 01:07:38,120
 I mean, I love that as a strategy for, like, for insulting someone is to compliment them.

818
01:07:38,120 --> 01:07:40,960
 Because then it's like, well, or makes themselves superior to you.

819
01:07:41,140 --> 01:07:46,440
 Like, because they have placed themselves in a position of judgment, it's like, hey, you did really great work on that.

820
01:07:46,820 --> 01:07:54,220
 Like, I just want to, you just want to go around just being like, that's such great stuff because I'm better than you.

821
01:07:55,460 --> 01:07:55,900
 Yeah.

822
01:07:56,060 --> 01:07:59,240
 What also makes the eventual insult way worse.

823
01:07:59,240 --> 01:08:07,160
 Like, if you're to, like, set someone up, like, really talk them up and then flip a switch and just see the light drain out of their face.

824
01:08:08,500 --> 01:08:16,960
 Well, I'll never forget, I'll never forget this, when Kristen Poirot, when she was faculty here and we went through, she was trying to get an essay published.

825
01:08:17,060 --> 01:08:20,840
